          "passage": "Several scholars have argued that conditions in England in the late ninth through early eleventh centuries—namely, burgeoning literacy amid\nrunning conflicts between England’s Anglo-Saxon kingdoms and Danish invaders—were especially conducive to the production of the Old English\nepic poem Beowulf, and they have dated the poem’s composition accordingly. It is not inconceivable that Beowulf emerged from such a context,\nbut privileging contextual fit over the linguistic evidence of an eighth- or even seventh-century composition requires a level of justification that\nthus far has not been presented.",
