          "category": "Command of Evidence",
          "questionType": "Command of Evidence",
          "difficulty": "Hard",
          "passage": "In ver tical inheritance, parents pass genes to their offspring, but in horizontal transfer (HT), one species, often bacteria, passes genetic material\nto an unrelated species. In a 2022 study, herpetologist Atsushi Kurabayashi and his team investigated HT in multicellular organisms—namely,\nsnakes and frogs in Madagascar. The team detected BovB—a gene transmitted ver tically in snakes—in many frog species. The apparent direction\nof gene transfer seems counterintuitive because frogs usually don’t survive encounters with snakes and so wouldn’t be able to transmit the\nnewly acquired gene to offspring, but the team concluded that BovB is indeed transmitted from snakes to frogs, either directly or indirectly, via\nHT.",
          "question": "Which finding, if true, would most directly suppor t the team’s conclusion?",
          "choices": [
            "BovB can be transmitted across frog species through HT.",
            "Parasites known to feed on species of snakes and fr ogs in which the BovB gene occurs also carry BovB.",
            "BovB cannot be reliably transmitted from a snake species to bacteria that are usually encountered by frog species.",
            "Frog species with BovB show few discernible advantages as compared with frog species that do not carry BovB."
          ],
          "answer": 1,
          "explanation": "Choice B is the best answer. If there are parasites that feed on both snakes and frogs, they could carry BovB from snakes to frogs. HT could\noccur “indirectly” through those encounters, which frogs are more lik ely to survive than snake encounters.\nChoice A is incorrect. The team’s conclusion specifically argues that BovB is transmitted from snakes to frogs via HT, and this choice doesn’t\nmention snakes. Choice C is incorrect. The team argues that BovB is transmitted from snakes to frogs via HT, and this answer choice discusses\na scenario in which the gene is not transmitted. Choice D is incorrect. Whether or not frog species with BovB are advantaged isn’t relevant to the\nteam’s conclusion about how the gene is transmitted.",
