          "category": "Central Ideas and Details",
          "questionType": "Central Ideas and Details",
          "difficulty": "Hard",
          "passage": "Philosophers note that many people have an intuitive sense that while we ought not to lie, there may be circumstances in which lying is\npermissible. If this intuition is correct and we lack an inviolable duty to speak truthfully, what grounds opposition to lying in the first place? Japa\nPallikkathayil has advanced one answer by appealing to a duty to respect others’agential interests: the possession of false beliefs constrains\nagency, and thus we ought not to impede the formation of true beliefs unless doing so prevents a greater constraint on someone’s agency or an\notherwise impermissible end.",
          "question": "Which choice best states the main idea of the text?",
