          "passage": "Birds of many species ingest foods containing carotenoids, pigmented molecules that are conver ted into feather coloration. Coloration tends to\nbe especially saturated in male birds’feathers, and because carotenoids also confer health benefits, the deeply saturated colors generally serve\nto communicate what is known as an honest signal of a bird’s overall fitness to potential mates. However, ornithologist Allison J. Shultz and\nothers have found that males in several species of the tanager genus Ramphocelus use microstructures in their feathers to manipulate light,\ncreating the appearance of deeper saturation without the birds necessarily having to maintain a carotenoid-rich diet. These findings suggest that\n______",
