          "difficulty": "Hard",
          "passage": "Mean Ticket Prices Chosen in Two Studies\nof Participative Pricing Messaging\nMean chosen price ($)\n80\n70\n60\n50\n40\n30\n20\n10\n0\n1 2\nStudy\npay what you can\npay what you think it’s worth\npay what you want\nParticipative pricing, in which purchasers choose the prices they pay for products, can enable sellers to capitalize on the heterogeneous values\nconsumers assign to the same goods and services, but doing so requires careful messaging. Annie Peng Cui and Jennifer Wiggins recruited 171\nparticipants (ages 18–60) online for an initial study and 83 students (ages 18–31) at a state university for a second study to test the effect of\nthree different messages—“ pay what you can, ” “ pay what you think it’s worth, ” and “ pay what you want”—on how much participants would pay for\nconcer t tickets. Their results illustrate both the heterogeneity of consumer valuations and how sellers can benefit by prompting consumers to\nconsider their own valuations: ______",
