            "guideWrongBreakdown": "How to Solve It: Identify the key evidence immediately before the blank or question. Turn that evidence into the next logical idea.\nEliminate answers that require outside facts, overstate the result, or contradict a detail in the text.\n\nCommon Trap: Making a leap beyond the evidence or choosing an answer that sounds plausible but is not directly supported.\n\nFinal Takeaway: Do not just choose a true statement; choose the statement that answers the exact question.\nCodex Instructions: Accurately Recreate SAT Graphs and Tables\nGoal\nRecreate every graph/table as a clean, SAT-style visual while preserving the exact data relationship tested by the\nanswer choices. Accuracy is more important than decoration.\nData extraction workflow\nFor each visual, manually record title, x-axis labels, y-axis title, units, scale range, tick interval, legend entries, series\ntype, marker style, and every plotted value. For tables, record column headers, row labels, units, and all values exactly.\nGraph recreation rules\nUse black/gray line art by default, matching SAT style. Use distinct markers and line styles rather than color alone.\nPreserve axis minimum/maximum, tick spacing, category order, legend wording, and units. Never smooth data unless\nthe original graph is smooth.\nTable recreation rules\nUse simple grid tables with bold headers. Preserve row/column order exactly. Keep units in headers, not repeated in\nevery cell unless the source does so. Do not round values unless the original values are approximate.\nValidation checklist\nAfter recreating, compare the new visual against the source: same title, same labels, same number of series, same\nvalues, same trend, same maximum/minimum, and same comparisons needed to answer the SAT question.\nImplementation hint\nBuild a reusable data object for every visual: {title, chart_type, x_label, y_label, y_min, y_max, y_tick, series:[{name,\nvalues, marker, linestyle}]}. Render from data, not from hard-coded pixels.\nQuality control\nExport a PNG preview and check it next to the original page. If an answer choice depends on “higher/lower,”\n“increased/decreased,” “same/about the same,” or “greater than,” verify those comparisons exactly.\nCodex Prompt Template\nYou are recreating SAT Reading and Writing visuals from uploaded question-bank PDFs. For each graph or table:\n1. Extract the visual’s title, labels, units, categories, series names, and all data values.\n2. Recreate the visual in clean SAT style using black, gray, dashed lines, solid lines, and distinct markers.\n3. Preserve the exact category order, axis scale, tick interval, legend labels, and table headers.\n4. Do not invent data, interpolate values, or change wording.\n5. After rendering, output a validation report comparing every recreated value and label against the original.\n6. Flag any uncertain value and explain what part of the source was unclear.\n7. Save both the recreated image and a machine-readable JSON/CSV data file.\nOverall Review\nPatterns in Mistakes to Watch For: Most errors in this set come from picking an answer that is true but not relevant,\nreading the wrong visual category, or choosing a claim that goes beyond the passage.\nStudy Notes: For graphs/tables, read titles, labels, units, and legends before choices. For inference questions, make\nthe smallest possible leap. For main idea questions, summarize the entire passage, not a single example.",
